  series = {IGSC '24},
  abstract = {Education technology (EdTech) is an important
tool for streamlining and improving course administration and
teaching. Many modern EdTech tools rely on cloud services to
host containerized applications. While this is convenient, it is
also costly in terms of both dollars and carbon emissions. We
propose the alternative approach of hosting containerized EdTech
applications on local clusters of upcycled Android devices.

We perform an evaluation of the Google Pixel Fold for
handling educational workloads. Our findings suggest that such
repurposed device could effectively bridge the gap between
mobile and traditional computing platforms in education, open
new avenues for accessible educational computing environments.
  },
